<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,303,712,738]" box="[189,303,712,738]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,712,738]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,712,738]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1399,759,891]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
The description is based on the parasites obtained from the sternites of the host insects; thalli growing on the wings are smaller (
<quantity box="[510,665,794,821]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.175" metricValueMax="2.55" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="mm" value="217.5" valueMax="255.0" valueMin="180.0">180–255 µm</quantity>
from foot to perithecial apex: 
<figureCitation box="[1045,1139,794,820]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[189,232,1715,1741]" captionTargetBox="[274,1314,265,1676]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[274,1314,265,1676]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 1. Photomicrographs of the new species of Rhizomyces Thaxt.: A. R. forcipatus W.Rossi &amp; Feijen sp. nov. (FI 4100a). B. Thallus of R. forcipatus sp. nov. from the wing of Teloglabrus sp. (FI 4125). C. Immature thallus of R. forcipatus sp. nov. showing the trichogyne and the basal cell holding firmly a piece of the exoskeleton of the host insect (FI 4099). D. R. tschirnhausii W.Rossi &amp; Feijen sp. nov. (FI 4091). E. Upper portion of the perithecium of R. tschirnhausii sp. nov. (FI 4090). F. R. ramosus W.Rossi &amp; Feijen sp. nov. (FI 4201a), amid the four mature perithecia, near the base of the stalk cells, it can be seen a fifth very immature perithecium bearing the trichogyne. G. R. ramosus sp. nov. (FI 4201a), the pyriform haustorium with remains of the host integument and cell I showing two primordia of new branches. Scale bars: 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3825123" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3825123/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
). The thalli observed on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Feijen" authorityYear="1983" box="[229,477,830,856]" class="Insecta" family="Diopsidae" genus="Centrioncus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jacobae">
<emphasis box="[229,477,830,856]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Centrioncus jacobae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are paler, more slender and longer on average (up to 
<quantity box="[1143,1238,829,856]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="mm" value="550.0">550 µm</quantity>
from foot to perithecial apex).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1399,930,1027]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<taxonomicName authority="Rossi &amp; Feijen, 2018" authorityName="W. Rossi &amp; Feijen" authorityYear="2018" box="[189,456,931,957]" class="Laboulbeniomycetes" family="Laboulbeniaceae" genus="Rhizomyces" kingdom="Fungi" order="Laboulbeniales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="forcipatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[189,456,931,957]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Rhizomyces forcipatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[467,561,931,957]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is distinguished from all the other species in the same genus by the peculiar shape and function of the basal cell. The latter is turned in, forming a ‘forceps’ which grasps a fold of the exoskeleton of the host insect (
<figureCitation box="[682,773,1001,1027]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[189,232,1715,1741]" captionTargetBox="[274,1314,265,1676]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[274,1314,265,1676]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 1. Photomicrographs of the new species of Rhizomyces Thaxt.: A. R. forcipatus W.Rossi &amp; Feijen sp. nov. (FI 4100a). B. Thallus of R. forcipatus sp. nov. from the wing of Teloglabrus sp. (FI 4125). C. Immature thallus of R. forcipatus sp. nov. showing the trichogyne and the basal cell holding firmly a piece of the exoskeleton of the host insect (FI 4099). D. R. tschirnhausii W.Rossi &amp; Feijen sp. nov. (FI 4091). E. Upper portion of the perithecium of R. tschirnhausii sp. nov. (FI 4090). F. R. ramosus W.Rossi &amp; Feijen sp. nov. (FI 4201a), amid the four mature perithecia, near the base of the stalk cells, it can be seen a fifth very immature perithecium bearing the trichogyne. G. R. ramosus sp. nov. (FI 4201a), the pyriform haustorium with remains of the host integument and cell I showing two primordia of new branches. Scale bars: 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3825123" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3825123/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1399,1067,1199]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<taxonomicName authority="Rossi &amp; Feijen, 2018" authorityName="W. Rossi &amp; Feijen" authorityYear="2018" box="[189,455,1067,1093]" class="Laboulbeniomycetes" family="Laboulbeniaceae" genus="Rhizomyces" kingdom="Fungi" order="Laboulbeniales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="forcipatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[189,455,1067,1093]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Rhizomyces forcipatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[464,557,1068,1094]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
bears a superficial resemblance with 
<taxonomicName box="[1010,1153,1068,1093]" class="Laboulbeniomycetes" family="Laboulbeniaceae" genus="Rhizomyces" kingdom="Fungi" order="Laboulbeniales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="crispatus">
<emphasis box="[1010,1153,1068,1093]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">R. crispatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the latter species has a stockier habitus, a more luxuriant appendage, a distinctly smaller and darker cell III, a darker and subconical tip of the perithecium, and it obviously differs from the new species in the shape of the basal cell.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1398,1239,1300]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
The presence of this fungus was already reported on various species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Speiser, 1910" authorityName="Speiser" authorityYear="1910" box="[1037,1348,1239,1265]" class="Insecta" family="Diopsidae" genus="Centrioncus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1037,1180,1239,1265]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Centrioncus</emphasis>
Speiser, 1910
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Feijen, 1983" authorityName="Feijen" authorityYear="1983" box="[189,482,1274,1300]" class="Insecta" family="Diopsidae" genus="Teloglabrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,328,1274,1300]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Teloglabrus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Feijen H. R." box="[335,482,1274,1300]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="3 - 137" refId="ref6237" refString="Feijen H. R. 1983. Systematics and phylogeny of Centrioncidae, a new afromontane family of Diptera (Schizophora). Zoologische Verhandelingen 202: 3 - 137." type="journal article" year="1983">Feijen, 1983</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Feijen H. R." box="[526,688,1274,1300]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="3 - 137" refId="ref6237" refString="Feijen H. R. 1983. Systematics and phylogeny of Centrioncidae, a new afromontane family of Diptera (Schizophora). Zoologische Verhandelingen 202: 3 - 137." type="journal article" year="1983">Feijen (1983)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1398,1340,1614]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<taxonomicName authority="Rossi &amp; Feijen, 2018" authorityName="W. Rossi &amp; Feijen" authorityYear="2018" box="[189,454,1340,1366]" class="Laboulbeniomycetes" family="Laboulbeniaceae" genus="Rhizomyces" kingdom="Fungi" order="Laboulbeniales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="forcipatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[189,454,1340,1366]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Rhizomyces forcipatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[462,553,1340,1366]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is found on several species of the genera 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Speiser" authorityYear="1910" box="[1050,1193,1340,1366]" class="Insecta" family="Diopsidae" genus="Centrioncus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1050,1193,1340,1366]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Centrioncus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Feijen" authorityYear="1983" box="[1252,1391,1340,1366]" class="Insecta" family="Diopsidae" genus="Teloglabrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1252,1391,1340,1366]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Teloglabrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This is remarkable, since the species of these genera occur in Afromontane forests and have very limited, allopatric distributions (
<bibRefCitation author="Feijen H. R." box="[567,713,1411,1437]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="3 - 137" refId="ref6237" refString="Feijen H. R. 1983. Systematics and phylogeny of Centrioncidae, a new afromontane family of Diptera (Schizophora). Zoologische Verhandelingen 202: 3 - 137." type="journal article" year="1983">Feijen 1983</bibRefCitation>
). The rate of parasitism came to 17%; however, this figure was lowered by the large 
<taxonomicName authority="Feijen, 1983" authorityName="Feijen" authorityYear="1983" box="[508,923,1446,1472]" class="Insecta" family="Diopsidae" genus="Teloglabrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sanorum">
<emphasis box="[508,761,1446,1472]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Teloglabrus sanorum</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Feijen H. R." box="[772,923,1446,1472]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="3 - 137" refId="ref6237" refString="Feijen H. R. 1983. Systematics and phylogeny of Centrioncidae, a new afromontane family of Diptera (Schizophora). Zoologische Verhandelingen 202: 3 - 137." type="journal article" year="1983">Feijen, 1983</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
sample of young flies. In female flies, 
<taxonomicName authority="Rossi &amp; Feijen, 2018" authorityName="W. Rossi &amp; Feijen" authorityYear="2018" box="[189,341,1482,1508]" class="Laboulbeniomycetes" family="Laboulbeniaceae" genus="Rhizomyces" kingdom="Fungi" order="Laboulbeniales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="forcipatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[189,341,1482,1508]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">R. forcipatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[350,442,1482,1508]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
was only found on the wings. In male hosts, the thalli were found on the wings (79%) and on the sterna (30%). Thalli were most often found on both wings together (61%), followed by right wing only (32%). 90% of thalli found on the sterna of males flies were on the left hand side (
<tableCitation box="[197,288,1588,1614]" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="6.[189,258,268,294]" captionText="Table 2. Prevalence of R. forcipatus W.Rossi &amp; Feijen sp. nov. on host species of Centrioncus Speiser, 1910 and Teloglabrus Feijen, 1983. Given are: totals of hosts examined (♀ and ³), totals with Rhizomyces Thaxt., infection location. (n. a. = not available)." pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Table 2</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
